Jetpack Compose simplifies UI creation, but integrating it with MVVM (Model-View-ViewModel) architecture involves changes compared to XML-based systems. This blog focuses on understanding how to implement **ViewModel** and **LiveData** in Compose, how they work together, and compares it to XML-based MVVM implementations.

> 
**For detailed understanding on MVVM in Android, please visit my seperate blog.**

Lets take an example to understand, MVVM using Jetpack compose. On page load we make API call and after 200 response, UI is populated.

**MVVM Flow **

- Activity will have object of ViewModel, that will be used to call the method of a ViewModel from `onCreate()` of Activity(thats the page load).
- ViewModel will further call the repository method.
- Repository makes API call, sends data back to ViewModel through callback.
- ViewModel process the data and set to LiveData defined in it.
- LiveData is getting observed in activity, it fetches the data and set to the UI.

# 1. ViewModel Instantiation

In Jetpack Compose, the recommended way to instantiate a `ViewModel` is using the `viewModel()` function provided by the **androidx.lifecycle.viewmodel.compose** library. It integrates seamlessly with the `ComponentActivity` or `NavHost` for lifecycle-aware ViewModel instances.

val userViewModel: UserViewModel = viewModel()This ensures that the `UserViewModel` is scoped to the lifecycle of the activity or composable, automatically handling recreation and configuration changes.

## Comparison with XML-based ViewModel Instantiation

In XML-based MVVM, the ViewModel is typically instantiated using **ViewModelProvider** in the Activity or Fragment:

val userViewModel = ViewModelProvider(this).get(UserViewModel::class.java)In Compose, the declarative approach with `viewModel()` eliminates boilerplate code while ensuring lifecycle management.

# 2. Implementing ViewModel and LiveData

Lets implement a `ViewModel` that exposes a list of users via **LiveData**.

import androidx.lifecycle.LiveDataimport androidx.lifecycle.MutableLiveDataimport androidx.lifecycle.ViewModelclass UserViewModel : ViewModel() { // Backing property for LiveData private val _users = MutableLiveData<List<String>>() val users: LiveData<List<String>> get() = _users init { // Simulating data loading loadUsers() } private fun loadUsers() { _users.value = listOf("Alice", "Bob", "Charlie") }}
- `**_users**`: Backing property for **MutableLiveData** (mutable state that can be updated).
- `**users**`: Exposed as immutable **LiveData** for the UI to observe.

> **If you are familiar with MVVM with XML view, here there is NO change. Also no change in repository so skipping that part in above code snippet.**

# 3. Using ViewModel and LiveData in Compose

In Jetpack Compose, the `observeAsState()` extension is used to observe **LiveData** from a ViewModel. It converts the LiveData into a Compose state object, ensuring automatic recomposition.

import androidx.compose.runtime.Composableimport androidx.compose.runtime.livedata.observeAsStateimport androidx.compose.foundation.layout.*import androidx.compose.foundation.text.BasicTextimport androidx.compose.ui.Modifierimport androidx.compose.ui.unit.dp@Composablefun UserScreen(userViewModel: UserViewModel) { // Observe LiveData from ViewModel val users = userViewModel.users.observeAsState(emptyList()) Column( modifier = Modifier .fillMaxSize() .padding(16.dp) ) { users.value.forEach { user -> BasicText(text = user) Spacer(modifier = Modifier.height(8.dp)) } }}
- `**observeAsState()**`: Converts LiveData into Compose-friendly state for observation.
- **Recomposition**: When the LiveData changes, the `UserScreen` recomposes automatically to reflect the updates.

# Integrating the ViewModel in Activity
Set up your activity to use Compose and provide the `UserViewModel`:

import android.os.Bundleimport androidx.activity.ComponentActivityimport androidx.activity.compose.setContentimport androidx.lifecycle.viewmodel.compose.viewModelclass MainActivity : ComponentActivity() { override fun onCreate(savedInstanceState: Bundle?) { super.onCreate(savedInstanceState) setContent { // Instantiate the ViewModel val userViewModel: UserViewModel = viewModel() // Pass the ViewModel to the Composable UserScreen(userViewModel) // } }}
```
import androidx.compose.foundation.layout.*import androidx.compose.foundation.lazy.LazyColumnimport androidx.compose.material3.Textimport androidx.compose.runtime.Composableimport androidx.compose.runtime.livedata.observeAsStateimport androidx.compose.ui.Modifierimport androidx.compose.ui.unit.dpimport androidx.compose.ui.text.font.FontWeightimport androidx.compose.ui.unit.spimport androidx.compose.ui.graphics.Color@Composablefun UserScreen(userViewModel: UserViewModel) { // Observe LiveData from ViewModel val users = userViewModel.users.observeAsState(emptyList()) LazyColumn( modifier = Modifier .fillMaxSize() .padding(16.dp) ) { items(users.value.size) { index -> Text( text = users.value[index], modifier = Modifier .padding(8.dp) .fillMaxWidth(), fontSize = 18.sp, fontWeight = FontWeight.Medium, color = Color.Black ) } }}
```
The ViewModel is instantiated using the `viewModel()` function and passed to the `UserScreen` composable. No extra wiring is required for lifecycle handling.

**Hope this blog makes you little more comfortable in Jetpack Compose.**

Happy coding!!
